article.description: Agnieszka Kulaga scored 17 points and Aimee Litka added 13, including a 3-pointer that ignited a 19-5 spurt to end the game and give Valparaiso a 71-60 victory over Purdue (No. 23 ESPN/USA Today, No. 21 AP), the third straight loss by the Boilermakers.
article.headline: Valparaiso beats Purdue for first time in 11 tries
article.linkText: Valpo hands No. 23 Purdue third loss in a row
article.story:
VALPARAISO, Ind. -- Purdue has lost its shooting touch.

The Boilermakers (No. 23 ESPN/USA Today, No. 21 AP) had their worst shooting game for a third consecutive outing and lost their third straight, only on Wednesday night it wasn't to a ranked opponent. Valparaiso held Purdue to 31 percent from the field while the Crusaders finished the game on a 19-5 run to beat the Boilermakers 71-60.

Purdue coach Sharon Versyp said her team missed too many wide open shots.

"Layups after layups after layups," she said. "You've got to make shots."

It was Valparaiso's first win in 11 tries against Purdue and its first win ever against a ranked opponent.

"I think that's every little girls dream to either be on Purdue or beat Purdue," said Valparaiso forward Whitney Farris, who is from Kokomo, Ind. "We accomplished that, so I think it's big time."

Valparaiso guard Aimee Litka, who is from South Bend, said the Crusaders knew Purdue didn't respect them.

"They didn't think much of us coming in and we knew that. So we came out and we showed them who we were. We proved them we're a better team," she said.

Versyp denied her team overlooked the Crusaders, saying her squad remembered narrowly beating Valparaiso 65-62 last year. She said the Boilermakers needed someone to step forward and make a shot, but no one did.

"We still don't have that person," she said. "We're just not stepping up and making plays."

Lindsay Wisom-Hylton, Purdue's leading scorer this season at 15.3 points a game, played just nine minutes in the first half because she was in foul trouble and was 2-of-9 shooting in the second half. Both baskets came in the first 2:30 of the second half, as she finished with 10 points.

While Purdue couldn't find someone to make a big shot, the Crusaders had three players come up big down the stretch. It started when Litka, who hit a 3 with 2 seconds left in the half to cut the lead to 34-30 at intermission, made her third 3-pointer of the game with 3:43 left to tie the score at 55.

"I knew the shot clock was going down so I just got my feet set and shot a wide-open 3, what I do best," she said.

Sylwia Zabielewicz followed that up with a three-point play, catching a rebound with one hand under the basket and then throwing the ball back over her shoulder as she was fouled by Natasha Bogdonova to give Valparaiso the 58-56 lead.

"I have no idea how I did that. But it went through," Zabielewicz said.

Then Farris came up with a rebound and a basket. The Crusaders finished the Boilermakers off by making 11 of 12 free throws. Valparaiso was 30-of-39 from the free-throw line while Purdue was 16-of-22.

Agnieszka Kulaga led the Crusaders with 17 points, making 9-of-10 free throws, Litka added 13 points and seven rebounds Launa Hochstetler scored 13.

Brittany Rayburn led Purdue with 19 points, but was just 2-of-7 for seven points in the second half, and Lakisha Freeman added 15 for Purdue.

Versyp said her team needs to get tougher.

"I think our post players are very, very weak. They're soft. So we have to change that mind-set."

The Boilermakers have one game left against Iona before beginning Big Ten play. She said the pressure should be off her team now.

"We're supposed to be good and we're not," she said. "So now there's no expectations and hopefully we can just settle down, relax and play."
